15, 4.8.14, 4.7.18, 4.6.19, 4.5.22, 4.4.23, 4.3.24, 4.2.28, 4.1.31, 4.0.31, 3.9.32, 3.8.34, 3.7.34).\";}i:2;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2020-4048\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.4.2\";s:11:\"description\";s:433:\"In affected versions of WordPress, due to an issue in wp_validate_redirect() and URL sanitization, an arbitrary external link can be crafted leading to unintended/open redirect when clicked. This has been patched in version 5.4.2, along with all the previously affected versions via a minor release (5.3.4, 5.2.7, 5.1.6, 5.0.10, 4.9.15, 4.8.14, 4.7.18, 4.6.19, 4.5.22, 4.4.23, 4.3.24, 4.2.28, 4.1.31, 4.0.31, 3.9.32, 3.8.34, 3.7.34).\";}i:3;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2020-4049\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.4.2\";s:11:\"description\";s:504:\"In affected versions of WordPress, when uploading themes, the name of the theme folder can be crafted in a way that could lead to JavaScript execution in /wp-admin on the themes page. This does require an admin to upload the theme, and is low severity self-XSS. This has been patched in version 5.4.2, along with all the previously affected versions via a minor release (5.3.4, 5.2.7, 5.1.6, 5.0.10, 4.9.15, 4.8.14, 4.7.18, 4.6.19, 4.5.22, 4.4.23, 4.3.24, 4.2.28, 4.1.31, 4.0.31, 3.9.32, 3.8.34, 3.7.34).\";}i:4;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2020-4050\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.4.2\";s:11:\"description\";s:516:\"In affected versions of WordPress, misuse of the `set-screen-option` filter\'s return value allows arbitrary user meta fields to be saved. It does require an admin to install a plugin that would misuse the filter. Once installed, it can be leveraged by low privileged users. This has been patched in version 5.4.2, along with all the previously affected versions via a minor release (5.3.4, 5.2.7, 5.1.6, 5.0.10, 4.9.15, 4.8.14, 4.7.18, 4.6.19, 4.5.22, 4.4.23, 4.3.24, 4.2.28, 4.1.31, 4.0.31, 3.9.32, 3.8.34, 3.7.34).\";}i:5;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2020-11030\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.4.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:465:\"In affected versions of WordPress, a special payload can be crafted that can lead to scripts getting executed within the search block of the block editor. This requires an authenticated user with the ability to add content. This has been patched in version 5.4.1, along with all the previously affected versions via a minor release (5.3.3, 5.2.6, 5.1.5, 5.0.9, 4.9.14, 4.8.13, 4.7.17, 4.6.18, 4.5.21, 4.4.22, 4.3.23, 4.2.27, 4.1.30, 4.0.30, 3.9.31, 3.8.33, 3.7.33).\";}i:6;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16781\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:256:\"In WordPress before 5.3.1, authenticated users with lower privileges (like contributors) can inject JavaScript code in the block editor, which is executed within the dashboard. It can lead to an admin opening the affected post in the editor leading to XSS.\";}i:7;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-20041\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:212:\"wp_kses_bad_protocol in wp-includes/kses.php in WordPress before 5.3.1 mishandles the HTML5 colon named entity, allowing attackers to bypass input sanitization, as demonstrated by the javascript&colon; substring.\";}i:8;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-20042\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:214:\"WordPress before 5.3.1 allowed an attacker to create a cross-site scripting attack (XSS) in well crafted links, because of an insufficient protection mechanism in wp_targeted_link_rel in wp-includes/formatting.php.\";}i:9;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-20043\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:201:\"WordPress before 5.3.1 allowed an unauthenticated user to make a post sticky through the REST API because of missing access control in wp-includes/rest-api/endpoints/class-wp-rest-posts-controller.php.\";}i:10;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16773\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:412:\"In WordPress versions from 3.7 to 5.3.0, the function wp_targeted_link_rel() can be used in a particular way to result in a stored cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerability. This has been patched in WordPress 5.3.1, along with all the previous WordPress versions from 3.7 to 5.3 via a minor release. Automatic updates are enabled by default for minor releases and we strongly recommend that you keep them enabled.\";}i:11;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16788\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.3.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:507:\"In WordPress versions from 3.7 to 5.3.0, authenticated users who do not have the rights to publish a post are able to mark posts as sticky or unsticky via the REST API. For example, the contributor role does not have such rights, but this allowed them to bypass that. This has been patched in WordPress 5.3.1, along with all the previous WordPress versions from 3.7 to 5.3 via a minor release. Automatic updates are enabled by default for minor releases and we strongly recommend that you keep them enabled.\";}i:12;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17669\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:178:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 has a Server Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability because URL validation does not consider the interpretation of a name as a series of hex characters.\";}i:13;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17670\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:158:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 has a Server Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability because Windows paths are mishandled during certain validation of relative URLs.\";}i:14;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17671\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:130:\"In WordPress before 5.2.4, unauthenticated viewing of certain content is possible because the static query property is mishandled.\";}i:15;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17672\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:101:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 is vulnerable to a stored XSS attack to inject JavaScript into STYLE elements.\";}i:16;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17673\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:136:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 is vulnerable to poisoning of the cache of JSON GET requests because certain requests lack a Vary: Origin header.\";}i:17;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17674\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:93:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 is vulnerable to stored XSS (cross-site scripting) via the Customizer.\";}i:18;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-17675\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:143:\"WordPress before 5.2.4 does not properly consider type confusion during validation of the referer in the admin pages, possibly leading to CSRF.\";}i:19;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16217\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:99:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 allows XSS in media uploads because wp_ajax_upload_attachment is mishandled.\";}i:20;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16218\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:53:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 allows XSS in stored comments.\";}i:21;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16219\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:56:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 allows XSS in shortcode previews.\";}i:22;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16220\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:148:\"In WordPress before 5.2.3, validation and sanitization of a URL in wp_validate_redirect in wp-includes/pluggable.php could lead to an open redirect.\";}i:23;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16221\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:61:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 allows reflected XSS in the dashboard.\";}i:24;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16222\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:163:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 has an issue with URL sanitization in wp_kses_bad_protocol_once in wp-includes/kses.php that can lead to cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\";}i:25;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2019-16223\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.2.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:74:\"WordPress before 5.2.3 allows XSS in post previews by authenticated users.\";}i:26;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2019-9787\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.1.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:467:\"WordPress before 5.1.1 does not properly filter comment content, leading to Remote Code Execution by unauthenticated users in a default configuration. This occurs because CSRF protection is mishandled, and because Search Engine Optimization of A elements is performed incorrectly, leading to XSS. The XSS results in administrative access, which allows arbitrary changes to .php files. This is related to wp-admin/includes/ajax-actions.php and wp-includes/comment.php.\";}i:27;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2019-8943\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"5.0.4\";s:11:\"description\";s:301:\"WordPress through 5.0.3 allows Path Traversal in wp_crop_image(). An attacker (who has privileges to crop an image) can write the output image to an arbitrary directory via a filename containing two image extensions and ../ sequences, such as a filename ending with the .jpg?/../../file.jpg substring.\";}i:28;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20147\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:128:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, authors could modify metadata to bypass intended restrictions on deleting files.\";}i:29;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20148\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:293:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, contributors could conduct PHP object injection attacks via crafted metadata in a wp.getMediaItem XMLRPC call. This is caused by mishandling of serialized data at phar:// URLs in the wp_get_attachment_thumb_file function in wp-includes/post.php.\";}i:30;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20149\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:230:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, when the Apache HTTP Server is used, authors could upload crafted files that bypass intended MIME type restrictions, leading to XSS, as demonstrated by a .jpg file without JPEG data.\";}i:31;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20150\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:119:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, crafted URLs could trigger XSS for certain use cases involving plugins.\";}i:32;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20151\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:288:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, the user-activation page could be read by a search engine\'s web crawler if an unusual configuration were chosen. The search engine could then index and display a user\'s e-mail address and (rarely) the password that was generated by default.\";}i:33;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20152\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:123:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, authors could bypass intended restrictions on post types via crafted input.\";}i:34;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2018-20153\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:147:\"In WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1, contributors could modify new comments made by users with greater privileges, possibly causing XSS.\";}i:35;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2019-8942\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.9\";s:11:\"description\";s:381:\"WordPress before 4.9.9 and 5.x before 5.0.1 allows remote code execution because an _wp_attached_file Post Meta entry can be changed to an arbitrary string, such as one ending with a .jpg?file.php substring. An attacker with author privileges can execute arbitrary code by uploading a crafted image containing PHP code in the Exif metadata. Exploitation can leverage CVE-2019-8943.\";}i:36;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2018-5776\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.2\";s:11:\"description\";s:111:\"WordPress before 4.9.2 has XSS in the Flash fallback files in MediaElement (under wp-includes/js/mediaelement).\";}i:37;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2017-17091\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:225:\"wp-admin/user-new.php in WordPress before 4.9.1 sets the newbloguser key to a string that can be directly derived from the user ID, which allows remote attackers to bypass intended access restrictions by entering this string.\";}i:38;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2017-17092\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:202:\"wp-includes/functions.php in WordPress before 4.9.1 does not require the unfiltered_html capability for upload of .js files, which might allow remote attackers to conduct XSS attacks via a crafted file.\";}i:39;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2017-17093\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:211:\"wp-includes/general-template.php in WordPress before 4.9.1 does not properly restrict the lang attribute of an HTML element, which might allow attackers to conduct XSS attacks via the language setting of a site.\";}i:40;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:14:\"CVE-2017-17094\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.9.1\";s:11:\"description\";s:178:\"wp-includes/feed.php in WordPress before 4.9.1 does not properly restrict enclosures in RSS and Atom fields, which might allow attackers to conduct XSS attacks via a crafted URL.\";}i:41;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9061\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:203:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, a cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerability exists when attempting to upload very large files, because the error message does not properly restrict presentation of the filename.\";}i:42;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9062\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:98:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, there is improper handling of post meta data values in the XML-RPC API.\";}i:43;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9063\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:147:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, a cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerability related to the Customizer exists, involving an invalid customization session.\";}i:44;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9064\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:178:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, a Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF) vulnerability exists in the filesystem credentials dialog because a nonce is not required for updating credentials.\";}i:45;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9065\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:102:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, there is a lack of capability checks for post meta data in the XML-RPC API.\";}i:46;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-9066\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.5\";s:11:\"description\";s:104:\"In WordPress before 4.7.5, there is insufficient redirect validation in the HTTP class, leading to SSRF.\";}i:47;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6814\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:351:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3, there is authenticated Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) via Media File Metadata. This is demonstrated by both (1) mishandling of the playlist shortcode in the wp_playlist_shortcode function in wp-includes/media.php and (2) mishandling of meta information in the renderTracks function in wp-includes/js/mediaelement/wp-playlist.js.\";}i:48;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6815\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:108:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3 (wp-includes/pluggable.php), control characters can trick redirect URL validation.\";}i:49;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6816\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:140:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3 (wp-admin/plugins.php), unintended files can be deleted by administrators using the plugin deletion functionality.\";}i:50;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6817\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:123:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3 (wp-includes/embed.php), there is authenticated Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) in YouTube URL Embeds.\";}i:51;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6818\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:113:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3 (wp-admin/js/tags-box.js), there is cross-site scripting (XSS) via taxonomy term names.\";}i:52;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-6819\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.3\";s:11:\"description\";s:272:\"In WordPress before 4.7.3, there is cross-site request forgery (CSRF) in Press This (wp-admin/includes/class-wp-press-this.php), leading to excessive use of server resources. The CSRF can trigger an outbound HTTP request for a large file that is then parsed by Press This.\";}i:53;O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"CVE_ID\";s:13:\"CVE-2017-5610\";s:19:\"versionEndExcluding\";s:5:\"4.7.2\";s:11:\"description\";s:24